commit_message:
Separate configuration based on test environment

Added:
- ARTIFACTS variable to store all test artifacts
  under single directory
- yaml config generation based on environment variables
- NAILGUN_CONFIG variable in run_tests.sh and settings.py

Commands used for testing:
  TEST_NAILGUN_DB=nailgun1 ARTIFACTS=/tmp/test_runs/1 \
  UI_SERVER_PORT=8011 FUELCLIENT_SERVER_PORT=8021 ./run_tests.sh

  TEST_NAILGUN_DB=nailgun2 ARTIFACTS=/tmp/test_runs/2 \
  UI_SERVER_PORT=8012 FUELCLIENT_SERVER_PORT=8022 ./run_tests.sh

Change-Id: If03dddee9a8259a80b526a53fe61a79c544c72a4
Closes-Bug: #1282565
Closes-Bug: #1334180

commit_message:
Eager-load Stack.raw_template for Stack.load

Whenever a stack is loaded from the database to perform a
parser.Stack.load, the raw_template should be prefetched to
avoid an extra sql query being performed.

However there are many calls to db_api.stack_get which do not need
to access Stack.raw_template, so the default behaviour is to
lazy-load it.

This change reduces the queries for a Stack.load from 3 to 2, so it
contributes to Related-Bug: #1306743

Change-Id: Ie6dad6ea4b1655a99e97a9ac2b7c00018406cd91

commit_message:
Fetch all db resources in one query

Instead of calling resource_get_by_name_and_stack once for every
resource in the stack, db_api.resource_get_all_by_stack is called
only once for all resources.

This reduces the number of sql queries during a describe_stack_resource
call to 3:
1. load the stack
2. load the template
3. load the resources

This is a big improvement over the start of this patch series, which
is 2 queries plus:
* 1 per resource in the stack
* 1 per access to a resource metadata attribute
* 1 per access to a resource data value

There is probably still potential to reduce queries from 3, but this
may well be a fix for
Partial-Bug: 1306743

Change-Id: I80be5d3de8744813d974f2e9860c148ad258f385

commit_message:
resource_get_all_by_stack returns a dict

This changes the returned results of resource_get_all_by_stack
to be a dict keyed by name, instead of a list of resources.

There appear to be zero uses of resource_get_all_by_stack so this
should have no effect on existing code, but it will be a more useful
form to consume the resources in a stack.

This change also prefetches resource data, as for
resource_get_by_name_and_stack

Change-Id: I1cc0ea7cf4852cc2407b3ada9ede7b5f6d1cc682

commit_message:
Refactor DB resource fetching from Resource to Stack

By moving this database call to the stack, this allows a future
change to adopt a loading strategy which avoids one sql call
per resource.

Change-Id: Ie29edaf3ffc0a332db421ad01edfa7445eb806e5
(manually merged from cherry-pick 9f01b9bc1a69a4843d3c9361cd990104613eed40)

commit_message:
Do not query database for every metadata_get

This change stores the rsrc_metadata locally when the Resource object
is created so that the database is not queried every time
metadata_get is called. There are some instances where the metadata
must come from the database (eg, polling for waitcondition signal) so
an optional refresh arg is added to metadata_get to force a database
refresh of the stored rsrc_metadata.

This results in one less sql query for every time metadata_get is called,
which will help the optimising effort for
Related-Bug: #1306743

Change-Id: Iad2d810c299347ae3b6a4a8329bbd314ee4b5c16

commit_message:
Use resource methods for metadata get/set

The current approach of using the Metadata descriptor
class has some issues including:
* Unintended database queries on accessing a metadata attribute
* get/modify/set patterns since the attribute isn't backed by a real dict
* lack of control over whether to fetch metadata locally or from the db

This change creates Resource methods metadata_get and metadata_set to use
for reading and modifying resource data. This is a refactoring change only so
there should be no change in behaviour.

This change will help in the future with
Related-Bug: #1306743

Change-Id: I7cd87a071ac410a388d787f132c9aee194030714
(manually merged from cherry-pick 96791aaa107b54908e3c7a7531d96f08cb17acd8)

commit_message:
Do not initialise stack_user password

Since Server implements this property with @property decorators,
setting password to None has the side-effect of writing None to
the resource data.

This change fetches the password with getattr instead.

Change-Id: I1107ee9710ec8520d7231c5b8b711e21b4183a34

commit_message:
Prefetch data in resource_get_by_name_and_stack

This loads resource and resource data in a single query, which means
one less sql query per stack resource in a call to describe_stack_resource.

Change-Id: Ic2e1ab68cf651f290be75206fd5c0c841de4ef82
Related-Bug: #1306743

commit_message:
Optional data for resource_data_get_all

resource_data_get_all queries the database for the data, and
transforms the results to a decrypted dict.

If the data is already loaded then it is unnecessary to do the
database query again.

This change allows data to be passed in as an optional argument.
If the passed data is not None then no database call will be made
and the dict transformation will occur on passed data.

Change-Id: I579225d9a3f3b038e0ca41a5900c58413d6e25ac
Related-Bug: #1306743

commit_message:
Move retry of prep_resize to conductor instead of scheduler

Prep_resize in Compute Manager calls back Scheduler prep_resize if
an Exception is raised. There is no sense of calling back the
scheduler, it should call Conductor instead.

Implements blueprint move-prep-resize-to-conductor

Change-Id: I2131843c291f5bd01eb4dbd6c8f36a9218120c19

commit_message:
Disable multi_host for nova-network with vCenter

- In HA setup with vCenter nova-network runs on OpenStack controller
  nodes.  We must be sure that nova-network service has single running
  instance among all controllers, otherwise VMs would see multiple
  gateways/DHCP servers in their network.  By default multi_host is
  enabled in HA mode and nova-network will run on every controller.

Partial implements: blueprint vcenter-hv-full-scale-support

Change-Id: I9cb7e1deaa0e533ce81e5f24159600493b25196f

commit_message:
Implement cleanup functionality for nova-network OCF script

* implement nova_network_cleanup() function
* determine network segmentation type that nova-network uses (for now
  only FlatDHCPManager supported)
* depending on IP protocol version flush certain iptables chains
* try 3 times to remove all IP addresses assigned to 'flat_network_bridge'
  (usually called 'br100')
* call nova_network_cleanup() during start, we need to be sure that
  there are no garbage when we start
* call nova_network_cleanup() when nova-network failed in
  nova_network_stop(), we need to stop dnsmasq, flush IP addresses on
  'br100' bridge and iptables rules, so thath VMs would not see two
  gateways/DHCP servers in their network
* call nova_network_cleanup() after successfull service stop
* check that 'ip', 'iptables' and 'ip6tables' binaries are available

Change-Id: I098afe269e55a2809ca230b2d6c3ec60c669cb8c
Partial implements: blueprint vcenter-hv-full-scale-support

When not using common-venv the venv will not exist until after the
horizon install.

We also want to rewrite the manifest after changing the contents of
the venv, to track what is installed.

This is not added to the horizon requirements file as it is an

commit_message:
Move python-memcached install after venv install

When not using common-venv the venv will not exist until after the
horizon install.

We also want to rewrite the manifest after changing the contents of
the venv, to track what is installed.

This is not added to the horizon requirements file as it is an
optional requirement based on whether memcached is being used or not.

Change-Id: I37b2c5bd95b6d6b484986b957e2866c2b57a5b4c
Closes-Bug: #1344014

commit_message:
Use VIF details dictionary to get physical_network

Modify mlnx_direct plug and unplug to retrieve physical_network
from VIF details dictionary if network meta dictionary does not contain
physical_network. This will serve ML2 case following the guidelines to
populate vif_details dictionary with attributes required for port plugging.

Change-Id: I0d97bc875be2fff18087c78accef3ec81c059c4b
Closes-Bug: 1304872

commit_message:
check ephemeral disk format at libvirt before use

Add ephemeral disk format at libvirt. There is no check before
so it will be used directly. This patch adds valid check function
and validate it before eph disk was used in virt layer.

Change-Id: I1934573e79f126e725cef4848b15c11a595161c9
Closes-Bug: #1293880

commit_message:
XenAPI: VM diagnostics for v3 API

For V3 API the diagnostics will have the format defined at:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Nova_VM_Diagnostics

This will support backward compatability with the existing APIs

Part of the blueprint v3-diagnostics

DocImpact

Change-Id: I8377f86a97ca554028e4ca8c1c1af7fd5643cc2e

commit_message:
Fixes hyper-v volume attach when host is AD member

The domain name gets added to the initiator name used by the host
if it's an Active Directory member.

Currently the method which gets the initiator name does not take
this into account when retrieving the default initiator name.

Trying to use a wrong initiator name will lead to an exception when
trying to log in to the according iSCSI target.

This patch simply appends the domain name (when the host is an AD
member) to the initiator name used to log in to iSCSI targets.

Closes-Bug: #1328870

Change-Id: Ifbe762c685e46081059a01043431b2c4ac5473fc

commit_message:
Added npm-shrinkwrap.json to lock down package versions

Also overrides version of bower for grunt-bower-task,
because all bowers <1.3.8 became buggy.
See https://github.com/bower/bower/pull/1403

Change-Id: I24fb24967b4870b5c6291b3f48451ef69e0bbe44
Closes-Bug: 1341156

commit_message:
Handle tcp requests correctly in mdns

Tcp requests have an additional length field before the payload.  This
is not the case with udp requests.  In addition, tcp responses also
need to have the length field at the start of the response.

For now we handle only one packet tcp requests.

Change-Id: Iaf0e45c02a3a6bf627eb6a5dd7aa21f401d6ceef
Closes-Bug: 1344131

commit_message:
Adds option to select a different subnet when adding 'vip'

With this fix, 'AddVip' from the dashboard gives user an
option to select a different subnet than the 'pool' subnet
and then creates a 'vip' with an ip (provided/next available)
from the selected subnet.

Change-Id: I25f36090c5fb739256b62a88915f6414e39a915f
Closes-Bug: #1285504

commit_message:
Add create and update times for trove components

Currently trove doesn't show created and updated
timestamps on databases and backups - this is
inconsistent with other dashboard components such
as compute and images

Add created and updated timestamps to details
page of databases and backups.
Backups was already display a 'Created At'
timestamp so also made the wording and formatting
of this consistent

Change-Id: Ia6011db3693471602328e6d471ca2064e882354d
Closes-Bug: #1336865

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-19 02:32:17.000000000', 'message': "Add APIv3 support to make host optional on evacuate.

In the event of an unrecoverable hardware failure, support needs to
relocate an instance to another compute so it can be rebuilt.
  [*] Bump v3 version of evacuate to set host argument optional.

DocImpact: The evacuate target host is now optional. If
'host' field is not sent in the request, the scheduler
will determine the target host. This will include
nova client changes ( on the proper commit ) to support
this new optional parameter.

Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Change-Id: I907ea4ef39cfad50a48cb80bceba217fdf482f6e
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Andres Buraschi <andres.buraschi@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anuj Mathur <anujm@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Navneet Kumar <navneetk@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claxton Correya <claxton@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Add APIv3 support to make host optional on evacuate.

DocImpact: The evacuate target host is now optional. If
'host' field is not sent in the request, the scheduler
will determine the target host. This will include
nova client changes ( on the proper commit ) to support
this new optional parameter.

Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Change-Id: I907ea4ef39cfad50a48cb80bceba217fdf482f6e
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Andres Buraschi <andres.buraschi@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anuj Mathur <anujm@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Navneet Kumar <navneetk@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claxton Correya <claxton@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Allow create volume group with block devices for lvm

Add new attribute, create_colume_group_type to allow
either create simple test volume based upon a file
(as existing support does),
or create volume group based upon block devices.

Change-Id: Ia81354f9fab9310c1b5e633d4ca05e434f9c2da6
Closes-Bug: #1321336

commit_message:
IPMINative set_boot_device persistent

The IPMINative driver was ignoring the 'persistent' argument passed to
the _set_boot_device(). Passing the 'persistent' parameter to the
set_bootdev() function is supported by pyghmi.

Change-Id: Idf3b3bed44fc6c537f75c631115e708d3355fef6

commit_message:
Fix service subnet capacity within service_instance module

Module 'service_instance' creates service_subnet per neutron_subnet,
current mask is 29, that allows take only 3 (three) ips for service
instances. Changed mask to 28, that allows take 11 (eleven) ips now
by default.
It allows us to use multibackend installation with drivers, that
depend on this module more reliably and provides possibility to
change this value in general.

Changes:
- added config option for network subnets mask with default value 28,
  instead of hardcoded 29.
- fixed related unittests

Change-Id: Ib58048832287a9f184317d2c92f0cc22e7f2a303
Closes-Bug: #1341711
Related-Bug: #1330391

commit_message:
Fix metaclasses assignment

'metaclass' with 'six' module should be added only using decorator for 'target'-class,
instead of attr assignment else 'target'-class won't see our custom metaclass.

this is fix after merged following commit:
https://github.com/stackforge/manila/commit/8c1a574de3e2e1b0da5f8ffa509284c84ca03264

Also added basic unittests.

Change-Id: I27cdddf32ec81c72a5f71ce8dca04f643a425b67
Closes-Bug: #1343207

>git remote update

>git pull

>git checkout <branch>
      (switch to your branch)
>git rebase master
      (should rebase against master and list conflicts)
>  edit any conflicts  and >git add  <filename>
>git rebase --continue
>git commit -a --amend

>git review

commit_message:
Update database and mysql dependency.

Now depends on mysql ~> 5.3 and database ~> 2.2.
The mysql-server recipe now uses the mysql cookbook
wrapper method.

Blueprint: move-to-mysql-v5
Change-Id: I74111ead1555c46d32c3e096c380fec27b3ef593

Add .gitreview file and update puppet coding style

create .gitreview file in devstack-vagrant project.
Put a trailing comma after the final resource parameter.

commit_message:
stunnel: Allow CA certificate to be specified

Allow a CA certificate to be specified in addition to a key and cert,
and automatically add it to the default system CA bundle.

This is required for sites which use their own Certificate Authority.

Partially implements: blueprint tripleo-ssl-overcloud

Full set of blueprint changes:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85098
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85099
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85100

Change-Id: Iaa5da8b1d9ffe72ae3959b7d3be4fb9b25c2f46e

commit_message:
Power driver for SNMP-enabled smart PDUs

A mechanism for remote control of node power by enabling or disabling
sockets on a rack power strip. The result will be a much wider
generalisation of the hardware that can be controlled by Ironic.

Change-Id: Ib16781eaa9737525c4d8a9231ecd9e72d7e2645e

commit_message:
Basic stunnel firewall configuration

Currently when using stunnel to terminate services using SSL (https) the
original http ports are still available to 'external' nodes.

Here we configure some basic firewall settings to disallow 'external'
connections to the services' http ports.

For now we allow connection from the nova compute nodes to the services'
http ports as using https for those connections is not there yet.

Change-Id: I017d70909d0462584ffc7b2e5ba27be765d78f18

Wouldn't it be better to just not listen on non-SSL ?"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-06-25 15:57:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Wouldn't it be better to just not listen on non-SSL ?

Yes, I agree that's where we want to get to eventually.

However, that may take a while as the nova compute nodes will need to be configured to connect via https to the various services (glance/keystone/neutron etc). That will involve a number of changes, so it could take a while.

This change is one of a set which allow us to configure some basic firewalling now -- to disallow external connections to the services' http ports while those other changes are being worked on.

If you're happy to wait for basic firewalling please let me know and I can abandon this patch - thanks."}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-07-21 09:25:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add nova_compute_ips to overcloud-source.yaml

Currently the nova compute nodes use http connections to the Glance,
Keystone, Neutron APIs.

If we firewall off non-local http connections to the controller node
connections from nova compute will fail.

We add a list of nova compute nodes' IPs. This list can be used by
iptables to allow connections from the nova compute nodes to the http
service ports.

This allows firewalling off all other external connections to non-SSL
ports.

Change-Id: I45611ba4307fa7b56c37d8fb7703d050e60fb92f

commit_message:
Add support for a neutron-based install

Update the trove-integration scripts to be able to install and
configure trove based on Neutron instead of Nova-network.

Co-authored by: Anna Shen <ruiyuan.shen@hp.com>

Partially-implements bp: neutron-support
Change-Id: Iec4773802034c42ddaeaa3c2f2c7cf4af3ee93ee

Change-Id: I720bfa0bb1b41a3d3ba4c4b00edd2c33bdaf165a
'}, {'created': '2014-07-11 14:00:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add kwargs to HttpError in apiclient.exceptions

kwargs, which are transmitted to HttpError in OpenStack clients, differs
with kwargs in HttpError from common code. HttpError should accept **kwargs,
which should help to provide backwards compatibility with original
exceptions in clients.

Change-Id: I720bfa0bb1b41a3d3ba4c4b00edd2c33bdaf165a
'}]
commit_message:
Add kwargs to HttpError in apiclient.exceptions

kwargs, which are transmitted to HttpError in OpenStack clients, differs
with kwargs in HttpError from common code. HttpError should accept **kwargs,
which should help to provide backwards compatibility with original
exceptions in clients.

Change-Id: I720bfa0bb1b41a3d3ba4c4b00edd2c33bdaf165a

commit_message:
Don't drop pre-existing database before tests

1. The database name is a random string, so shouldn't already exist.
2. If it *does* already exist, we quite likely want to throw an error
   rather than just delete it.
3. "drop database if exists non_existant_database" throws an error with
   mysqlconnector and a noisy-but-harmless warning with others.

(We could fix (3), if it was important)

For consistency, this also makes drop_database raise an error if the
database doesn't exist (or has been already deleted).

Closes-Bug: #1341906
Change-Id: I0c4a460088ffb7eb79cbf8594d2ff37fd70cf157

Maybe food for thought, but what in this is specific to openstack, seems like this logic would be better in sqlalchemy?'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-07-12 02:37:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

interpreting exceptions in an agnostic way as we are doing here has long been something that I don't think belongs in SQLAlchemy.   It's not possible to do completely as there are tens of thousands of exceptions, and it's not possible to do in a way that isn't surprising and/or broken on a regular basis when presented against the whole world of applications (as opposed to the extremely narrow immediate needs of openstack).   it would push a vast amount of logic upstream onto me directly.   Keeping it downstream means the scope is super limited instead of vast and limitless, and also that anyone here at openstack central can easily contribute to it.

that leaves maybe the "filter decorator" concept, squeezed between handle_error() (which *is* in SQLAlchemy) and the job of identifying/handling every possible exception.   It's about ten lines of code so, might be nice, then again people might never notice it and/or understand it when it's presented without context.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-07-17 14:12:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-17 14:12:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Implement new exception interception and filtering layer

Replace @_wrap_db_error() with an event-based system
that leverages the new SQLAlchemy handle_error() event.

The internal logic of @_wrap_db_error() is replaced by a
system of declarative filters, which is also expressed
on the testing side using a new test framework for these
conditions.

partially implement bp: use-events-for-error-wrapping
Closes-Bug: #1214341
Change-Id: Ib8c7f8d5c6f44c49a53dd6411adbf8aaaecb74be

subject: Implement the SQLAlchemy ``handle_error()`` event.

commit_message:
Implement the SQLAlchemy ``handle_error()`` event.

This event hook is to be released as of SQLAlchemy 0.9.7, and
supersedes the existing SQLAlchemy ``dbapi_error()`` event, which
is called upon interception of all DBAPI errors and other exceptions
that are raised within core Engine operations.  The new event offers
the ability to intercept all errors associated with statement execution
and result reception, not just DBAPI-level errors, and also supports
re-raising of the given exception with a replacement exception.

Here, we implement a compatible system that works in SQLAlchemy 0.8
and forward.

partially implement bp: use-events-for-error-wrapping
Change-Id: Ife52be4ae870739dc296742fa4aefb3e31c36be4

commit_message:
VMware: Convert vmops to use instance as an object

This is mostly mechanical, but it does expose what appears to be a bug
in the interaction between object.Instance's config_drive field and
configdrive.required_by(). object.Instance defines config_drive to be
a String, but configdrive.required_by() expects it to be a Boolean. In
assigning a boolean value to config_drive, it is cast to a String,
which evaluates as True when cast back to a Boolean. We therefore
update the tests which use config_drive to set either a String value,
or None, which is what other code does.

Note that Nova does not pass an Instance object to all driver methods,
so not all uses can be updated.

Change-Id: Ifc9ce5d96da30abfa09b608a9c8615ede1485a50

commit_message:
Add supported file system type check at virt layer

Currently nova doesn't check whether the file system type is supported
by virt layer(hypervisor) before use it. This patch adds current
support file system type definition then create a default check
function at virt layer. Following patches will do the real check
in different driver such as libvirt.

Change-Id: Ie4d876a48b36c1a53b171dd521bdeef868a31486
Partial-Bug: #1293880

commit_message:
Wrap eventlet's Timeout exception

Eventlet's Timeout was subclass of Exception. But at some point it
switched to BaseException. Now statements like

  except Exception as e:

do not catch it. Wrapping Timeout into our own one fixes this.

Change-Id: I90bf3b2335359e1f7f4c376e0e7292f18c75f162

commit_message:
Extend status_description column in Clusters tables

Convert column type to
 * Text for psql - unlimited size
 * LongText for mysql - max size 2^32

Also fixed template for autogenerated migrations: added a blank line to
avoid pep8 violation.

Closes-Bug: #1338933
Change-Id: Ie4c4f57aeb7ff03aa7f6077629f6463a136f8f4b

commit_message:
Updates xi:include link

OpenStack Documentation's (openstack-manuals) common folder has changes in the
name of the given file. Updates the URL to point to the new file name.

Updates the fallback URLs too. This is temporary fix since lot of patches are
getting stuck.

Change-Id: I62c463a730ae32b1a74475f69e4576d48e6cea8d

commit_message:
Always run sysctl through sudo

Some distros (Debian) don't put sbin in PATH for regular users.

To avoid rootwrap overhead in common cases, a best-effort attempt at
running /sbin/sysctl (without sudo) is tried first to see if the option
is already enabled.

Change-Id: I2466cf5d8fafb441e0594f20c148dcf6a764368d
Closes-Bug: #1300800

commit_message:
Update port binding when unshelve instance

When unshelve instance, it should update the attached port also.
This patch invoke network_api.migrate_instance_finish to update
the port's binding info.

Change-Id: Iaa77163dde5494154d67ef392142669d70c3e643
Closes-Bug: #1306922

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Adds backup/restore support for couchbase

Backup strategy:
- Save bucket metadata config (as json file) to /tmp/backups
- This is needed on restore to create the destination buckets
- Handles root enabled case by also saving /tmp/secret_key to /tmp/backups
- Use cbbackup to do the backup
- /tmp/backups will be zipped up, encrypted, and sent to Swift
- If no buckets, backup will error out

Restore strategy:
- If /tmp/backups/secret_key exists, set root password
- Iterate through bucket metadata config (json file) and use Couchbase
  REST API to create each bucket
- Wait until bucket finishes creating
- Use cbrestore (which requires destination buckets to be manually
  created first) to do the restore
- cbrestore can only restore one bucket at a time

Change-Id: Iaf4370dcc978df68e7d01c6f63795eaf50aac89d
Implements: blueprint backups-single-instance-couchbase

commit_message:
Add Backup/Restore support for Couchbase

Backup strategy:
- Save bucket metadata config (as json file) to /tmp/backups
- This is needed on restore to create the destination buckets
- Handles root enabled case by also saving /etc/couchbase/secret_key to /tmp/backups
- Use cbbackup to do the backup
- /tmp/backups will be zipped up, encrypted, and sent to Swift

Restore strategy:
- If /tmp/backups/secret_key exists, set root password
- Iterate through bucket metadata config (json file) and use Couchbase
  REST API to create each bucket
- Wait until bucket finishes creating
- Use cbrestore (which requires destination buckets to be manually
  created first) to do the restore
- cbrestore can only restore one bucket at a time

DocImpact
backup_namespace and restore_namespace were in the default conf group, now they are per datastore

Change-Id: Iaf4370dcc978df68e7d01c6f63795eaf50aac89d
Implements: blueprint backups-single-instance-couchbase

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-07 13:42:26.000000000', 'message': 'Allow to delegate some vlan provider attributes choice to neutron

PartialSpecsVlanTypeDriver is an alternative type driver for VLANs.
It allows to delegate the choice of some provider attributes to
neutron when creating vlan provider-networks. In practice,
provider:physical_network and provider:segmentation_id choices can
be delegated to neutron, in such case neutron will try to find a
network in tenant network pools which respects provided provider
attributes.

DocImpact

When using partial-specs-vlan type driver for VLANs, the attributes
provider:physical_network and provider:segmentation_id become
optional on provider-network creation, neutron will try to find a
valid network in tenant network pools.

Related to blueprint provider-network-partial-specs

Change-Id: I2c52c71167edaa153b2e04681273e2f1be8d03aa

commit_message:
Add partial specs support in ML2 for vlan provider networks

ML2 provider networks partial specs let admins choose some provider
network attributes and let neutron choose remaining attributes. This
change provides the implementation for VLAN provider networks.

In practice, for VLAN provider networks provider:physical_network
and provider:segmentation_id choices can be delegated to neutron,
in such case neutron will try to find a network in tenant network
pools which respects provided provider attributes.

DocImpact

Related to blueprint provider-network-partial-specs
Partial-Bug: #1330562

Change-Id: I2c52c71167edaa153b2e04681273e2f1be8d03aa

commit_message:
Specification for FWaaS changes for DVR

Spec addresses the changes required for FWaaS to work with
DVR to handle:
* Perimeter Firewall support on N - S traffic
* Ensure that E - W DVR traffic is not broken

Implements: blueprint neutron-dvr-fwaas

Change-Id: I2ea7e39b03655cf8ff5fe533b50c5d33ade6720f

Improve ch_messaging-security.xml

Use markup for passwords and indicate that it should be replaced.
Add missing line in programlisting.
Change IP to all-caps.
Rewrap all paragraphs to avoid overlong lines.

commit_message:
Refactoring build-app and unittest-app

Created app-common
Replaced with tlog function with TLOG
Added elapsed function, replaced print_end_timestamp
Replaced get_image_id with app_glance_id
Replaced run_timed_command with PRUN
Removed use of EXIT_STATUS
Replaced argument -z tests with $# test
Prepended docker unittest with PRUN
Removed commented code and other cleanup

Change-Id: Ibd9374524541c49d20625d58db1c005351d79c8f

(7 comments)

A lot of good work has gone into this proposal, but I'm concerned that in its current form, it may be difficult to adequately review in time for the spec approval deadline.

I'm wondering if the scope of this proposal can be reduced significantly by focusing on the minimal changes necessary in order to support dynamic segments for use in conjunction with the hierarchical port binding BP (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/106185/). Basically a way to instantiate pools of VLAN segments from which dynamic segments can be allocated/returned seems to be what's needed. Could the refactoring of responsibilities between the TypeManager and TypeDrivers and support for customizable segment types be deferred to a separate BP?"}, {'account_id': 107, 'date': '2014-07-19 00:52:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

(3 comments)

It seems to me this specification proposes three different features that might better be specified and implemented separately - dynamic segments, refactoring to allow customizable segment properties, and keeping track of whether a network was created as a tenant or provider network. Implementing the dynamic segments is the priority for Juno, and I'm not sure the other two parts are well enough specified at this point. I'm happy to work with Arvind during implementation to see if the dynamic segment support can be implemented first, or whether it really depends on (at least some part of) the refactoring he proposes."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-21 01:49:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: -Verified

commit_message:
Add argparse for RHEL6

python2.6 doesn't have argparse, required by outfilter.py.  This
package is a dependency on cloud-init, so this problem is often masked
in many testing environments.

Change-Id: Ia564f1b8a7b540faa7bbdbd1a1a290c591901682

Revert "Store clients in context"

This commit caused a regression in tripleo when trying to signal
waitconditions.
This reverts commit de8b071acf21fe054267619124ac1a0374496185.
Fixes-bug: #1344079

commit_message:
Move plugin.delete_port call out of transaction

This might fix a few cases of lock wait timeouts.

Change-Id: Iaa656a8582b2ff3ec55709bbe47b1ac9f5fc2a99
Closes-Bug: #1342166

I have worked on similar tasks for the NSX plugin.
Needless to say, sync issues are always more difficult than how they look.
This blueprint actually seem to have a rather large scope, and can perhaps be broken into several smaller blueprints.

For instance there are several aspects:
- rolling back neutron resources on VSM failures
- detecting when the backend goes out of sync with the neutron db
- synchronizing resources between neutron and VSM backend (mono directional, bidirectional, etc.)
- handling disaster recovery scenario (need to recreate configuration against a new VSM backend)

As it is, this blueprint in my opinion is a candidate for deferral to K release. This is not only for technical reasons, but also from considerations regarding perceived priority for this work item and work items already approved for juno.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-14 14:44:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Config option to control visibility of cisco-policy-profile

Currently, cisco-policy-profile resources must be explicitly assigned to tenants.
This blueprint proposes adding a config option to Cisco N1KV plugin to control the
visibility of these resources.

The options may be True/False.
Selecting True would allow tenants access to all the cisco-policy-profile resources
without the need for explicit assignment.
The False option would require explicit assignment of a cisco-policy-profile resources
to a tenant.
Default value is True.

Change-Id: Id69023e46960a48bc6f223d7522980df66842e0f

commit_message:
Remove deprecated nova_create_flavors.sh script

nova_create_flavors.sh has been deprecated for over a year (since 2013-05-07)

Removing the script, since it is not documented in any current READMEs
or on the Openstack wiki.

Change-Id: Ib6031c2518b8e6d43bb692e0f687a2e287ec494f
Partial-Bug: 1338066

commit_message:
Increase dashboard installation introduction clarity

Moved content associated with the administration guide
to the "next steps" section of the Horizon install guide.

Added content to the Horizon installation introduction
to increase clarity, and match the OpenStack
installation documents. Unified xml file header.

Change-Id: I3a1f9fc1e1515d22a6b3e7ddc19df1db3ecfd884
backport: none
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements

commit_message:
Precise-->Trusty patches for several guides

As Juno will not be supported on Ubuntu 12.04 Precise,
this patch changes all references to 14.04 Trusty, which will
support the next 4 releases.
Updated section_ubuntu_example.xml for consistency.

Change-Id: Ib52513db38b17240026e6a278e8c97c0438358ec

commit_message:
Move cli generated files out of common

There's no shared usage for these files, so move them into a
subdirectory of cli-reference.

Call the subdirectory generated and add a README so that it's clear that
these are generated files.

Fix also .gitignore to only ignore some top-level directories.

Change-Id: Ifb455a8640cc7e735ed81563b438d68522e73ded

accepts DatastorePath objects instead of literal strings.

commit_message:
Breakdown CSS: split out the resource browser

Now that everything has been converted to scss, splitting out the
individual components of our CSS can and should begin!

In an effort to do small changes (to keep them mergable and reviewable)
I'm only splitting out the resource browser stuff.  I'm trying to
balance the style that Maxime has used throughout the previous reviews
relating to this blueprint while also not changing everything that can
be changed.

Change-Id: Ibc9fb11163883498384e963210067e9600fbca9d
Partially-Implements: blueprint css-breakdown

should be replaced by 'for example'.

commit_message:
Revert "Add missing image to instance booted from volume"

This reverts commit c3191cf0ba5ad3dc2df8da2a2bf5c9d270fde9d9.

The change needs to be thought out some more, i.e. why isn't
compute_api.get_all just loading up the image_ref value on the instance
object rather than calling a helper method from the servers extension to
the instance object which just calls back to compute_api, seems very
roundabout, plus isn't it a v3 API issue also?

Conflicts:
	nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py

Due to: 826aed0 Use oslo.i18n

Change-Id: I6abbfdfa786c3d98065c969e7f9d7d5830caf7e8
Closes-Bug: #1343689

A quick question: if the existing password gets leaked somehow and the operator needs to change to a new password in the config files, will there be a problem?'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-06-28 16:03:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Or if the swift backend fills up and we need to swap in a new swift backend with different creds would that be possible?'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-06-28 18:47:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

i have a new patch coming up with better tests.

but to answer ur questions, yes that will be possible.

because we are plugging in the swift user and key into the url based on ur config value at that given point of time.

previously we had issues like if password changes, there was no way to update swift locations, and they were all invalid now. 

if I am missing soemthing please let me know. thanks for the review!'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-06-28 18:48:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-06-28 19:14:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-06-28 19:27:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2013-06-28 20:04:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

In general this looks good to me.  Some overly critical comments:  

There is something about basing the decision to replace creds on their current string (hidden_*) that rattles me.  I realize that it will be quite unlikely that the actual creds will meant that string but all the same it would be nice to have that decision made on something more definitive like a 'scrub' field in the DB perhaps (that way other storage modules could take advantage of it).  Or if nothing else perhaps a config option to replace the default string (hidden_*).

Also I am trying to see how this would work with anonymous swift urls.  Either because the operator is dealing with a store that doesn't use a password (perhaps host based authentication) or because an anonymous/temporary swift url was added to the location.  From eye-balling it I think this will be fine but it might be good to have a test for it."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-28 20:05:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-06-29 05:29:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@iccha-sethi, I have a critical concern about this change, under the change the sensitive info will be removed from location string from the DB record when store add image and the info will be inserted (by parse_uri()) to location when the store using the location to do something, such as api/repo code call store get(), delete().

so under this design with current you changed, the client side will could not get correct/available location string even admin enable it with 'show_image_direct_url' (or 'show_multiple_locations', incoming) option, api client will always get scrubbed location string. this will caused client such as nova could not consume image by location url directly, it need always need download it from glance. I think this is a /really/ bad idea.

Actually under my plan, nova will could consume image by location directly if there's a. have available 'image handle' and image has particular location url. please refer: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/image-multiple-location (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/33409/2/nova/virt/images.py)

So, IMO, can we give a option to glance to allow admin disable this scrub behavior? or you have other idea about this? thanks."}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-07-01 09:43:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Iccha,

Many thanks for the password change clarification!

I'd still be interested to know if concerns such as Mark W's here:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1100220/comments/5

are addressed by this change. ie the ability to simultaneously upload to a 'new' swift while being able to continue to download from an 'old' swift.

Somewhat related: I believe it is currently possible to specify a custom swift location in a header when uploading an image. If so are these custom locations (which will have different creds than in the conf files) handled?

Also, its possible to encrypt the location with a 'metadata_encryption' config option. Again I'd just like to double check that if that option has been enabled the migration will still work ok.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-07-01 17:12:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Stuart you bring up a good case case I had not considered. I can think of a long drawn solution, let me know what you think or if you have any suggestions.
The goal is to preserve the older swift credentials and a way to indicate that these need to be plugged into which location when it is obtained from db.
possibly having 
[swift_store_1]
user..
key..
scrub_swift_credentials = True
scrub_prefix_user = 'hidden_user_store_1'
scrub_prefix_key = 'hidden_key_store_1'

[swift_store_2]
user..
key..
scrub_swift_credentials = True
scrub_prefix_user = 'hidden_user_store_2'
scrub_prefix_key = 'hidden_key_store_2'

current_swift_store = swift_store_2"}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-07-01 17:18:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Zhi,

How would the client get the location? Is it directly from glance database?'}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-07-01 17:38:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Oh and for the encrypt metadata option Stuart, that is still an option. The only reason I was avoiding it is it still means we are storing credentials in some form in the db.'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-07-01 21:56:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

A few notes:

1) I'm with Stuart--we should still be able to support multiple backend accounts/containers. Unfortunately, I can't think of any way to do this other than requiring a glance configuration like the following:

<id1>: user1, pass1
<id2>: user2, pass2
...

and then running a find/replace on all the swift locations in the db, erroring out if the substitution for a given user/pass combination is not provided in the config. I also don't love reusing the user info part of the httpurl, and would rather we just tack on the credentials id at the end of the url, after a space or some other url-terminating character. AKA, "swift://user1:pass1@authhost.example.com:8770/glance/foo" would become "swift://authhost.example.com:8770/glance/foo id1".


@zhiyan, the explicit purpose of this change is to enable always exposing location data even to less trusted parties. To make this work, nova and glance are going to have to share configuration for determining the actual user credentials, assuming nova wants to talk directly to the store. Is sharing configuration a suitable solution?


Regarding metadata encryption, I think the main thing that is needed is for us to decrypt the location from the database before performing the substitution.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-09 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-08-12 12:29:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

A comment on the approach rather than the code.

If glance is deployed in an automated way (eg chef, puppet) there may be an issue
with this approach with regard to changing the swift backend password. (Though no worse than
the existing code).

Lets imagine you have two glance-api servers and an original password 'p1'.
You wish to change the password to 'p2'. You will not necessarily be able to
synchronize the writing out of the two glance-api.conf files, eg chef may write
the first node's config file at 12:00:00 but the second node's config file some time
later, eg at 12:07:40. In the mean time requests to the second node for old images
will fail. Similarly the synchronization of the password change itself with the config
file change may be problematic for automated deploys.

What would be required for this to work would be two passwords which are 'live' at
the same time. During the deploy both would be active, when the deploy is complete
the old password would be retired. Keystone does not provide this functionality, but
keystone v3 does provide something similar; user access keys:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/access-key-authentication

It is possible to have more than one 'live' user access key available at the same point
in time. If glance switched to using 'user access keys' to acquire a token for
swift operations it would be possible to automatically deploy a credential change
(ie move from one access key to a new one).

Should we consider this approach? (Here? In a separate blueprint?)"}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2013-08-15 17:15:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hey Sridevi, bunch of comments inline

Maybe before you address those it would be good to just lay out a little more in a  high level overview of this change. I'm wondering things like:

As a deployer, am I forced to update my configs for this change to work?
Are swift_store_user and swift_store_key config options just deprecated or no longer work?
How does this work for multi-user swift deployments?"}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-10-09 14:33:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 34.'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-10-09 14:36:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 33: (12 inline comments)

Hi Alex,

Thanks for your review comments.

No, it is not necessary to have swift_store_credentials confs. The code uses swift_store_user and swift_store_key as the default credentials.
swift_store_credentials, if given will override the default value.
However, swift_store_user and swift_store_key configs are deprecated.

Hi,

Have we thought through the implications if the scrub user and scrub password  are leaked?

For example if they leak a user can then create an image (new image '123' say) while specifing a location of an existing image ('456') as follows:

image-create --location=swift+http://scrubuser:scrubpass/swift.com/456

Can a subsequent image-download for image '123' result inthe bytes of image '456' -- which
may be owned by another user -- being downloaded?

Similarly might this provide a path for replacing '456' with a new image (potentially with malware) using image-upload?

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 177, 'date': '2013-10-14 20:18:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 34: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

'}, {'account_id': 177, 'date': '2013-12-03 20:00:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 40: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(9 inline comments)

Hey Sridevi,

Sorry to hold up this patch even further. There are a few cases I think we need to take into account so we can maintain backwards compatibility and have everything working. The rest of this patch seems to work great so thanks so far.

Downloads

When using show_image_direct_url or show_multiple_locations config settings, the location returned remains scrubbed. This means that the location will not work as is and the client needs to replace the scrubbed values with real values. We can maintain backwards compatibility if we unscrub the location when doing an image show/detail.

* image-show with show_image_direct_url

direct_url       | swift+http://hidden_user_1:hidden_key_1@localhost:5000/v2.0/glance/45527114-487b-4737-8262-1ab26c123177 |

* image-show with show_multiple_locations

 locations        | [{u'url': u'swift+http://hidden_user_1:hidden_key_1@localhost:5000/v2.0/glance/45527114-487b-4737-8262-1ab26c123177', u'metadata': {}}] |



Uploads

The following two cases will insert the image location into the database without scrubbing them first. This means that the user will need to provide a location that is already scrubbed correctly, requiring them to know the current settings glance is using to scrub images.


* v2 PATCH set multiple locations

curl -i -X PATCH -H 'X-Auth-Token: $AUTH_TOKEN' -H 'Content-Type: application/openstack-images-v2.1-json-patch' -d '[{"path": "/locations", "value": [{"url":"swift+http://bah_tenant:bah_user:bah_pass@localhost:5000/v2.0/glance/1", "metadata": {}}, {"url":"swift+http://bah_tenant:bah_user:bah_pass@localhost:5000/v2.0/glance/2", "metadata": {}}], "op": "replace"}]' http:localhost:9292/v2/images/3d547f7d-1824-432b-94be-fc39435d45e3

will have those identical locations in the db.


* v1 setting location via update or create

glance image-create --name add-with-scrub-v1 --disk-format=vhd --container-format=ovf --location="swift+http://bah_user:bah_pass@localhost:5000/v2.0/glance/45527114-487b-4737-8262-1ab26c123177"'}, {'account_id': 177, 'date': '2013-12-03 20:14:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 40:

One more thing, when updating with multiple locations it will return a 400 bad request because it tries to talk to swift with the given location in order to validate it but the real credentials are not there.'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-12-06 07:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 41.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-06 08:59:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 41: Doesn't seem to work

A couple of thoughts on the current approach.

The current approach uses an 'in-band' method to signify that
the crendentials should be taken from the glance-api.conf file.
What I mean is that we use the existing 'location' format, but with a
special scrub user to signify 'take the credentials from the
config file'.

This approach means that the scrub user credentials are a
sort of 'pseudo' back end credential. If they leak it is possible
to use them (for example by setting the location) to access
other users' images. So, in some sense, the goal of this patch

 > The image locations table stores the swift url for images
 > which includes the user and key values. This if exposed
 > can cause security risk. 

is not achieved. We are still storing a form of credentials
in the database, which if leaked, allows user access to
images.

Also, if the scrub credentials are leaked and you wish to change
the scrub username/password this is a non-trivial task since
all images' metadata must be updated. While the scrub user credential
change is being performed some images would be offline as they would
not yet have been updated to the new scrub user/password. Ideally
all images should remain accessible in the event of any password
change.

A potential alternative 'out-of-band' approach may not have those
undesirable features.

For example, lets assume that swift+https://:/container/image is currently
an invalid location format. We could adopt this format to mean "take the
credentials from file". (The absent username/password and second ':' denotes
that we wish to take the credentials from the glance-api.conf file.)

We can forbid users directly setting the location to that format under
any circumstances. ie using --location to set to that format would
be forbidden. (The API would set an image's location to that format
on behalf of a user for a 'regular' upload.)

This out-of-band approach would mean:

 1) no credentials/pseudo-credentials in the database
 2) no pseudo-password change which would require a metadata update of all images.
 3) no pseudo-credentials to be leaked (which users
    can use nefariously)'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-12-06 12:14:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 40:

Hi Sridevi,

I misinterpreted your last question -- sorry.

(I thought you were asking about allowing ad hoc
credentials, unknown to the operator, for third party
stores.)

Note that what I'm advocating is not really a 'blank' location, but rather defining a new location format that enables whatever functionality we require (whatever that ends up looking like).

(One specific case I'm keeping in mind here is the case where an employee, who knows all creds, leaves the company. This requires a credentials change, which IMHO needs to be handled with zero downtime.)

I could see a variation on your current approach working
to allow multiple backend stores.
 
 swift+https://:@<store1_loc>/<container>/<uuid>

for each store keep a dictionary of creds:

 swift_store_credentials = {'<store1_loc>': 'jdoe:jdoe:a86850deb2742ec3cb41518e26aa2d89',
 '<store2_loc>': 'acct2:user2:586850deb2442ec3cb41518e26aa2d89'}

where <store1_loc> might be "store1.example.net:35357/auth/v1.0" for example.

Again, setting to a null credential format ("swift+https://:@") would be forbidden, in the same way
as a user setting a "file://" location format is forbidden for security reasons.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-12-12 12:13:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 43:

Thinking about the multi-store case a bit more it seems that currently we don't really have full support for where
you may want to bring a new backend swift store online. For example I don't this its currently possible if, say, your current store is http and the new one is https, or the current one resides in 'region a' while the new on resides in 'region b'.

It occurred to be that it would be possible to define a new location format as follows:

swift://<store>/<container>/<object>

"store" would denote which backend store we wish to use. We would then define the attributes of that store in the configuration.

That allows us to specify different credentials for each store, but also offers the flexibility to specify different regions or url endpoints. (Or even the potential -- with additional functionality -- to migrate from a single tenant store to a multi-tenant store).

For example if we wished to have two stores, 'store1' and 'store2' as follows:

-------
 #!/usr/bin/python

 store_dict = "{'store1' : {'credentials'    :'jdoe:jdoe:a86850deb2742ec3cb41518e26aa2d89', 'auth_url' :    'https://keystone1.example.net:35357/auth/v1.0'}, 'store2' : {'credentials'   : 'acct2:user2:586850deb2442ec3cb41518e26aa2d89', 'auth_url' :   'http://keystone2.example.net:35357/auth/v1.0', 'auth_version' : '2.0',   'region' : 'region-b', 'storage_url' : 'http://1.2.3.4:123'}}"

 stores = eval(store_dict)
 print "store1 creds", stores['store1']['credentials']
 print "store1 auth url", stores['store1']['auth_url']

 print "store2 creds", stores['store2']['credentials']
 print "store2 auth_url", stores['store2']['auth_url']
 print "store2 auth_version", stores['store2']['auth_version']
 print "store2 region", stores['store2']['region']
 print "store2 storage_url", stores['store2']['storage_url']
-----------

 store1 creds jdoe:jdoe:a86850deb2742ec3cb41518e26aa2d89
 store1 auth url https://keystone1.example.net:35357/auth/v1.0
 store2 creds acct2:user2:586850deb2442ec3cb41518e26aa2d89
 store2 auth_url http://keystone2.example.net:35357/auth/v1.0
 store2 auth_version 2.0
 store2 region region-b
 store2 storage_url http://1.2.3.4:123


actual examples of the locations might be:

swift://store1/glance_container/e7e96a8a-e2eb-47a5-8252-de3bff229686
swift://store2/glance_container/7d861618-ca2f-4f18-94e8-68c7ad4e2346

For this patch we would just focus on the credentials part of this, but with the added 'store' abstraction.'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-12-19 08:18:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 44.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-19 09:11:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 44: Works for me

Hi Sridevi, many thanks for your updated patch (and your patience over the series of patch sets).

I've a few high level queries.

1) There seems to be some prior support for a swift:// style of location (as opposed to swift+https:// or swift+http://).

I see it documented at the start of class StoreLocation as follows:

 "The swift+http:// URIs indicate there is an HTTP authentication
 URL. The default for Swift is an HTTPS authentication URL, so
 swift:// and  swift+https:// are the same..."

From a quick reading of your patch you don't seem to be migrating locations of this form "swift://" to this form "swift+https://".
Can you confirm if this is the case?

If so I think we need to also perform that transformation as part of the migration.

Otherwise the 'swift://' scheme is ambiguous. We want it to always mean 'take the credentials from file'. That way, for example, we can forbid a user from ever setting a location of the form 'swift://' (as we do with http://).'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2013-12-26 06:07:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 44:

'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-01-22 16:21:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 57:

Hi Sridevik,

Thanks for your updated patches.

I'd like to return to the issue of https+swift:// versus swift:// ...

First, a reminder that setting a "file://" location is forbidden:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/4602/5/glance/api/v1/images.py

This is to prevent users setting a location to something like "file://etc/passwd" which would allow access arbitrary files on the system. (A security hole).

I previously gave an example of an employee leaving an organisation. In this case, the operator will change the swift backend password to a new value (unknown to the ex-employee), but the 'store' name in the location (swift://<*store*>/<container>/<object>) will remain unchanged. Since the ex-employee still knows the store name he or she can set a new location using the known store name -- this will potentially allow access to any image data. (A security hole).

To prevent users setting 'store' style locations I think we need a way to disambiguate between 'system' set 'store' locations and user set arbitrary swift locations.

Previously I'd suggested using "https+swift://" for user specified locations and "swift://" for new-style system locations which specify a 'store' (using the format swift://<store>/<container>/<object>).

I hadn't reaslised that swift:// was already in use (it means the same thing as https+swift://). I had
thought that we would be able to tell that any location of the form 'swift://' was system set and specified a store in the config files ... but that's not the case. Also I thought that we would be able to disallow users setting a location of the format 'swift://' (to avoid the security hole).

I still think we need to allow users to continue to set https+swift:// style locations -- which will never map to a 'store', while having another format which tells us straight away 'this location is mapped to a configured "store"'. Users would be forbidden from using set location to set a 'store' style format (in the same way as setting to file:// is forbidden).

We could potentially migrate any existing locations of the form swift:// to https+swift:// -- this would allow us to use the swift:// form exclusively for 'store' style locations; it would also allow us to prevent users from setting locations of the form 'swift://'.

1) Do you agree that we need to prevent users setting a location which will be interpreted as a 'store' location (ie a location whose credentials and other parameters will subsequently be read from file)?

2) Do you think migrating swift:// and then using that format for our store is a good idea? or should we try something else, such as a new format altogether, eg something like 'swift+config://'.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-01-22 17:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 55: (3 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2014-01-23 13:00:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 57:

Hi Sridevi,

Thanks for your continued heroic work on this patch :-)

I think what we're doing here can benefit multi-tenant stores also.
I don't think it would be fair to ask you to make any code changes per se for
that, but if we changed some of the wording / config options that may make things
clearer in the future.

Let me try to explain where I'm coming from.

Right now (with this patch) we're using "glance-swift.conf" basically to store credentials for the single tenant store. However, in the future we could also use it to fully describe how to instantiate a swift client for any given swift store.

So, in the future we could potentially have something like:

  glance-swift.conf:
  [ref1]
  user = tenant:user1
  key = key1
  auth_url = http://auth123@example.com

  [ref2]
  multi-tenant = True
  swift_url = http://swift.example.com
  insecure = False

  [ref3]
  multi-tenant = True
  swift_url = http://swift2.example.com
  insecure = True
  
In this case we have a single tenant store like we have today (ref1), but also have multi-tenant stores (ref2, ref3), which take advantage of a new 'insecure' swift client option (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/69187). Note neither 'ref2' nor 'ref3' actually contain any credentials.

Do you think it would be ok to re-word some things so that the wording would be less specific to a single tenant store with credentials? Eg "Configuring Multiple Swift Accounts" would change to "Configuring Multiple Swift Stores".

(I'd be happy to pull down the patch and propose something if you'd be ok with that?)'}, {'account_id': 7531, 'date': '2014-02-17 05:10:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 60:

[{'created': '2013-06-27 21:14:22.000000000', 'message': 'Remove user and key from location in swift

can cause security risk. Hence this patch, santizies
that information out of the location before storing
and plugs it back in when it is required.

creating an image or updating it.

commit_message:
Remove user and key from location in swift

The image locations table stores the swift url for images
which includes the user and key values. This if exposed,
can cause security risk. Hence this patch, santizies
that information out of the location before storing
and plugs it back in when it is required.
Introduced a new configuration file that supports
multiple swift account references. It has the credentials and
authurl for each store.  It is specified using
'swift_store_config_file'.
In addition, this patch does the following things:

Differentiate user and system created swift location

Currently we do not differentiate between user created
locations and system created locations that have the account
reference. This patch introduces new scheme:
'swift+config' for this purpose.

Image create in V1 should validate the uri

This patch ensures that a store is not set while
creating an image or updating it.

Related to bp remove-sensitive-data-from-locations
Implements blueprint: support-multiple-swift-backends
Implements bp: v1-image-create-should-validate-the-location-uri
DocImpact

Flavors are an important Operator requirement so I am happy that this is being tackled. My understanding is that the flavor framework will manage devices from different vendors and allow users/operators to pick them with different criteria. Scheduling should be inspired and/or take advantage of scheduling as a service as offered by gantt. 

Looking at the code I am seeing a way to add arbitrary "tags" to a specific driver but I don't understand where a policy like all LB driver shall have the attribute algorithm of type, say, String, is enforced. Not that tags have the same name but a different data type. Also operator specific information like availability zones, region, etc, is not being considered. Can that be provided by the driver or is a component missing which would add those tags?

To develop powerful scheduling algorithm the tags and their respective values need to be known beforehand and the framework needs to enforce them. Gantt does that with specifically declaring them -- so "filters" can be developed which take them into consideration. 

To sum it up I don't see a way for an operator to add specific driver independent values (e.g. region, etc). I would like a way to enforce that certain values have been set by the driver to allow for complex scheduling.'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-05-01 03:23:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2014-05-01 15:02:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Proof of Concept flavor framework

The patchset illustrates the idea of flavors and how they are
connected with drivers/providers/service plugins/etc.

The usage and example plugin reside in test_flavor.py

commit_message:
Add commands for loadbalancer agent scheduling

Add commands that list loadbalancers on the agent and
list agents hosting loadbalancer.
These commands replace deprecated commands related to
loadbalancer pool scheduling

Change-Id: I1376aac3cca98100dcc3561e0048f6b29e832ddb

commit_message:
Add cli commands to manage loadbalancer instance

Add CRUD commands for loadbalancer resource.
Also add loadbalancer_id attribute to lb-vip-create
and lb-pool-create commands

Change-Id: I0522e034aa96f2629c0fd8e24f8930940303c1d9

'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

Needs documentation and comments explaining what the purpose of the loadbalancer resource is. With this code, it's not clear what benefit the loadbalancer resource gives the user of the Neutron LBaaS API, versus the existing API that ties a pool to a provider. All this does is change the pool ownership to the loadbalancer, which is itself tied to a single service provider.

There's no indication why this model -- if the same inflexible method of tying all resource creation to a statically file-configured service provider -- is any better than what exists today.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

Hi Eugene,

I did not felt it was not backward compatible. Indeed it looked to me you did API-level backward compatibility, but then I was reading on the ML archive that it seems there was a consensus around compatibility at CLI level, which would have been not ok.

I'm not a terminology expert, lb/loadbalancer still doesn't sound ideal but I'm happy with anything the community agrees one.

Deprecation process is pretty much about documenting an attribute as deprecated and then removing it in the next release.
-"}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I have looked at the code, and technically it look mostly fine except for a few things we can smooth over during subsequent review iterations.

It seems to me that at end you've gone for ensuring backward compatibility in the API and not on the CLI. I would second this decision, as the CLI is definetely not the only consumer of the neutron api. It is, in my opinion, just one consumer, not anymore important than any other consumer.

In the light of backward compatibility I would like to understand which attributes are going to be marked as deprecated in Icehouse, if any.

Also, this might come a little late, but the name "loadbalancer" sounds a bit repetitive, e.g.: /v2.0/lbaas/loabalancer would be a bit like v2.0/networking/network; this is a minor point but I would prefer using "instance".

Finally, my only concern is that it seems the discussion ended on the mailing list about two months ago without a clear indication regarding whether neutron lbaas should follow the libra model and whether backward compatibility should be handled as it's being done here.

Is there any further update from the subteam meetings which has not yet been shared on the mailing list, or which I failed to find?'}, {'account_id': 333, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Thanks Salvatore for looking into this,


As for backward compatibility, I thought that I've done it fully backward compatible, e.g. CLI is also backward compatible. Why do you have the feeling that it is not?

As for name of the instance, first of all, the prefix is /lb/ so it is not looking very repetitive (as /lbaas/loadbalancer), also 'instance' is a bit too broad term. So I'd prefer to stay with 'loadbalancer' unless you have stronger opinion.

As for discussion on backward compatibility, the most strong opinion came from tempest folks who think that stable API is good in itself and we should not change it unless absolutely required. It think that approach proposed in the patch (auto-creation and auto-deletion) is both satisfying compatibility and consistent.

And the last item: the only attribute that should be deprecated is 'provider' attribute of the pool. How should I mark it? Should it be comment or some doc bug?"}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

Hi Eugene,
I'm not talking about backward-compatible use of the API.
To rephrase the previous comment, if a user created an loadbalancer instance with an explicit API call (/loadbalancers), he wouldn't expect it get deleted with some side effect (eg. deletion of a pool). I don't think such a thing doesn't happen often with other OpenStack DB resources.  (Please correct me if I'm wrong.)"}, {'account_id': 9200, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: (1 inline comment)

What we will have is:
1. create a loadbalancer
2. create a pool, a vip, etc and deploy an LB
3. delete the LB created above
4. the loadbalancer created in step 1 magically disappears

I don't think the step 4 is what users generally expect. It's not mentioned in the BP or the wiki. It will be even more confusing if a user creates another LB in step 2'."}, {'account_id': 9200, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17: (2 inline comments)

Maybe I'm a bit noisy...

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Introduce Loadbalancer instance

This commit introduces loadbalancer instance into LBaaS API,
object model, driver interface, unit tests.
The purpose of LB instance:
1) envelope other main balancer resources such as vips and pools
That is needed to retain loadbalancer configuration as a tree
instead of a graph when multiple pools-vips relationship is
introduced. So Loadbalancer object becomes the root of the tree
instead of the Pool
2) Provide clear boundaries for loadbalancer configuration.
All objects that belong to one loadbalancer are deployed to one
device or agent and are handled with the same provider (driver)
3) Loadbalancer object becomes a 'mounting point' of attributes
associated with configuration such as provider, device, agent,
router.

The patch contains the following changes:
 - CRUD operations for loadbalancer resource
 - Autocreation of loadbalancer resource with the pool
 - Autodeletion of loadbalancer resource with vip or pool deletion
 (needed for API compatibility)
 - Corresponding changes in the driver API

Other changes:
 - provider attribute has moved to loadbalancer resource from the pool.
 E.g. provider attribute in the Pool object is deprecated, but returned
 for backward compatibility.
 - NiciraServicePlugin was fixed in order to preserve backward
compatibility of LBaaS API of Nicira Plugin

implements blueprint lbaas-service-instance
DocImpact
Change-Id: I2bcd98002ad359c713ba128cebe9125767ae88f8

2) Provide clear boundaries for loadbalancer configuration.

device or agent and are handled with the same provider (driver)
3) Loadbalancer object becomes a 'mounting point' of attributes

The patch contains the following changes:
 - CRUD operations for loadbalancer resource
 - Autocreation of loadbalancer resource with the pool
 - Autodeletion of loadbalancer resource with vip or pool deletion
 (needed for API compatibility)

commit_message:
Introduce Loadbalancer instance

This commit introduces loadbalancer instance into LBaaS API,
object model, driver interface, unit tests.
The purpose of LB instance:
1) envelope other main balancer resources such as vips and pools
That is needed to retain loadbalancer configuration as a tree
instead of a graph when multiple pools-vips relationship is
introduced. So Loadbalancer object becomes the root of the tree
instead of the Pool
2) Provide clear boundaries for loadbalancer configuration.
All objects that belong to one loadbalancer are deployed to one
device or agent and are handled with the same provider (driver)
3) Loadbalancer object becomes a 'mounting point' of attributes
associated with configuration such as provider, device, agent,
router.

The patch contains the following changes:
 - CRUD operations for loadbalancer resource
 - Autocreation of loadbalancer resource with the pool
 - Autodeletion of loadbalancer resource with vip or pool deletion
 (needed for API compatibility)
 - Corresponding changes in the driver API

Other changes:
 - provider attribute has moved to loadbalancer resource from the pool.
 E.g. provider attribute in the Pool object is deprecated, but returned
 for backward compatibility.
 - NiciraServicePlugin was fixed in order to preserve backward
compatibility of LBaaS API of Nicira Plugin

implements blueprint lbaas-service-instance
DocImpact
Change-Id: I2bcd98002ad359c713ba128cebe9125767ae88f8

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-15 16:22:42.000000000', 'message': "vmware: add namespace for diagnostics (v3 API only)

There is no formal definition for the VM diagnostics. For the
V2 API the diagnostics will be returned as they are today. For the V3
api the diagnostics will be prefixed with the driver namespace.

That is the diagnostics will be returned as follows:
{'vmware': {'key1': 'value1',
            'key2': 'value2',
             ...}}

This will support backward compatibility with the existing API's.

Part of the blueprint diagnostics-namespace

DocImpact

Change-Id: I6465ee6fc2edac0107e260297d9647c8a16b09ae

commit_message:
vmware: VM diagnostics (v3 API only)

There is no formal definition for the VM diagnostics. For the
V2 API the diagnostics will be returned as they are today.

This will support backward compatibility with the existing API's.

Part of the blueprint v3-diagnostics

DocImpact

Change-Id: I6465ee6fc2edac0107e260297d9647c8a16b09ae

commit_message:
Handle null JSON blobs

The JSON deserializer doesn't handle null values properly; it raises
a TypeError because it expects a string or buffer. This became apparent
after the supplier info update which added columns that would be null
for existing packages. Patch returns None from the JSON deserializer
in that case, and also refactors unittest base classes.

Change-Id: I6f31500d2dd1aaaf6a1fd26c1901666072d79776
Closes-Bug: #1342306

commit_message:
xenapi: virt unrescue method now supports objects

Commit 65ad230af5ece020822fa963dd30fd641a54ae91 ensured
that the compute API and manager are now getting objects
for the unrescue method.

This patch adds support to the virt driver code.

Change-Id: Ie6b587d3f89202a6987291bfaea88290241651f2

I don't think adding old scripts back is the way to go. It doesn't solve a problem, it just papers over it. Adding them back will create confusion for all who don't know why they are there.

My preferred solution is instead to get the proper solution in place soon -- I can help with that.

If we need a stop-gap measure, either link into the git history [1] or give the scripts a path that clearly indicates their purpose (e.g. temporary-old-scripts/Credentials.sh).

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/training-guides/plain/labs/openstack_scripts/Keystone/Scripts/Credentials.sh?id=b3b462260bd37cbceba0adccf6d6e81724622de7"}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-07-19 07:25:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Roger, we need these scripts for IceHouse release. The new scripts that you are taking about is going to go into Juno. I really thing this should be in here. I dont want to point to scripts in the history, seems to be bad practise.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-07-19 07:38:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

What does "Icehouse release" mean in this context? Icehouse happened without the install scripts working, and the new scripts can install the Icehouse release of OpenStack once they're done.

Unlike openstack-manuals, we don't have release branches in training-guides, so it's unclear to me when the old scripts, once re-added, can be removed from the head of the git tree.

I am going to change my vote to neutral to let those who are more involved with the guide decide.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-07-19 07:50:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Adds Keystone Scripts

Add keystone scripts to the docs basic-install-guide folder, till the labs
section is properly implemented.

Also modify links pointing towards the keystone scripts.

Change-Id: Ic1eea2bd814209eeef0e31ce7149711035c8d85e
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-guides
Fixes-bug: #1282056

commit_message:
Add python-ceilometerclient in requirements

With the addition of the ceilometer client in the scenario tests, the
python-ceilometerclient is missing. This patch adds it to the packages
to be installed in requirements.txt.

Change-Id: Icb667def3afb71d20bc7a90e6e031cf671adc321
Closes-Bug: #1337309

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 hosts API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
whole of Nova APIs.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: Ie252dce67f8e9d3292d8dad767b6113f7affcffd

(1 inline comment)

If we were only going to do serial console logging it wouldn't be the end of the world to use one binary per console. Looking down the road a bit this would be a great mechanism to use for granting intelligent access to console logs, or even r/w console access to VMs without VNC or spice. Running one binary per VM isn't ideal in that case. 

I think this would be better to be written in such a fashion that it wouldn't have to be rewritten later if someone wants to extend the console process youre building. 

I wrote something that did exactly this a few years ago. Two processes run, the console process and the UDS sentry. When the console process starts it binds a socket to listen from the sentry. Then it looks for all existing UDS for VMs and binds to them. For each one of those it spins off a child that will watch the UDS and write the output to the console log (which it rotates as necessary). The UDS sentry uses inotify to monitor the instances directories. After starting it will connect to the console daemon then begin watching the instances directory. When inotify detects that a new console UDS has been created it will send a bit across the pipe to the console sentry to tell it to refresh its console list. 

Then I extended the daemon to allow r/w access to the serial console. A client would connect to the daemon and after an  auth-ng process the client would be attached to the child, who would tee the client into the console session. The client could do whatever work they needed, and it would all be logged. 

I realize this is a departure from most of what you're trying to do here, but my point is that even if you don't do any of the other bits, it would be best to write this in such a way that it could easily be extended and enhanced, without a rewrite. 

I wrote this all in Perl, so I can't just forklift it over. But I could help write it in Python, if you're interested in any help?"}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-04-18 04:37:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)

Sorry this draft is a bit confusing... I did a quick edit to take into account feedback which made me believe this should be one process per hypervisor node, and I clearly missed spots. I'm fixing it now."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-04-25 06:03:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Abandoned
